[normal]&#xa0;[bold]School factors[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]I[bold]ntervention to improve white working class pupils’ attainment – the Government’s approach.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Action[bold]Detail[bold]Prioritising the most disadvantaged children through additional funding to increase their access to early years education, and support their attainment and progress through the 
[normal]pupil premium in schools
[normal]The two year old offer, which builds on the 3 and 4 
[normal]year old offer of funded early education; the Pupil Premium funding, including recent announcement for a primary uplift.
[normal]Setting high expectations of the quality and standards of education for all pupils, including the most disadvantaged, throughout their
[normal] education to 19
[normal]High quality teaching, reformed GCSEs, A levels and vocational qualifications, study programmes for 16 to 19 year olds and high quality Apprenticeships
[normal]Entrusting our teachers, head teachers and childcare professionals to use their autono
[normal]my to make the right decisions to meet the needs of their pupils, including the most disadvantaged
[normal]Schools deciding how to use the Pupil Premium, and the Education Endowment Foundation Toolkit, which provides cleared evidence based advice on what works 
[normal]in 
[normal]raising the attainment of disadvantaged pupils.
[normal]Holding schools and colleges to account for the outcomes they secure for their disadvantaged pupils, through a robust accountability system.
[normal]The Department has just consulted on primary and secondary account
[normal]ability, and launched a consultation on 16-19 accountability
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Impact of the Wolf Review[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Table 4: Modelled impact of Wolf recommendations on Key Stage 4 outcomes, 2012[bold]Currently, 58.3 per cent of pupils achieve the expected level at Key Stage 4 – this falls to 54.8 
[normal]per cent when Wolf reforms are applied to the data.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Chart [bold]9[bold]: Number of qualifications entered pre and post Wolf recommendations, split by type of qualification, 2012[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Fifty-six per cent 
[normal]of white FSM pupils entered 1 or more Wolf approved equivalent qualifications, compared to 47 per cent of all other pupils.
[normal] 
[normal]Six per cent of white FSM pupils entered 3 or more Wolf approved equivalent qualifications in 2012 – these pupils would only see 2 o
[normal]f these qualifications counted in the 5A*-C threshold measure
[normal]. Entry patterns for non-white FSM pupils are the same as for white FSM pupils, with 56 per cent entering 1 or more Wolf approved equivalents and 6 per cent entering 3 or more.
[normal]Table 5: Number of[bold] Wolf approved equivalent qualifications[bold]Overall, 96.7% of the approved equivalents entered by white FSM pupils achieved a pass grade (C or above); this compares to 97.9% for all other pupils.
