[normal]Department for Children, Schools and Families, 2010.
[normal] 
[normal]Dunne et al (2007) found that 51% of
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]FSM pupils were in the low ability sets, and 
[normal]23% in the high ability group in primary schools. This compares to 22% of non-FSM pupils in low ability groups and 43% in high ability groups. In secondary schools 38% of FSM pupils were in the lower ability sets and 20% in the higher ability groups. Howev
[normal]er, this compares to 22%
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]of non-FSM pupils in lower ability groups and 39% in the higher groups. The research suggests that this is due to setting being based in prior attainment.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] This figure is based on the size of the qualification – so where one qualification counts for 2 GCSEs, then it is counted twice in this figure.
[normal] 
[normal]Under Wolf reforms, qualifications are limited to 1 GCSE in size and are counted as such.
[normal] This figure falls t
[normal]o 6.2 entries per pupil on average, when the number of entries to approved equivalents is limited to 2 entries per pupil.
[normal] This is a count of qualifications, rather than their size (some qualifications can be worth the equivalent of 2 or more GCSEs, - her
[normal]e they have been counted as 1 qualification rather than taking into account their size).
[normal] In 2012-13, the eligibility criteria was extended to include all those who had been registered for FSM at any point in the previous six years (this was known as the 
[normal]Ever 6 rule)
